.TH SEATUYA 3 "2026-03-07" "seatuya 0.2.0" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
seatuya \- C library for local control of Tuya smart devices
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include <seatuya/seatuya.h>
.PP
.BI "const char *tuya_version(void);"
.PP
.BI "tuya_device_t *tuya_create(const char *" version ");"
.br
.BI "void tuya_destroy(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.PP
.BI "void tuya_set_credentials(tuya_device_t *" dev ","
.BI "    const char *" device_id ", const char *" local_key ");"
.br
.BI "const char *tuya_get_device_id(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "const char *tuya_get_local_key(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "const char *tuya_get_ip(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.PP
.BI "bool tuya_connect(tuya_device_t *" dev ", const char *" hostname ");"
.br
.BI "void tuya_disconnect(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "bool tuya_is_connected(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "bool tuya_reconnect(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.PP
.BI "bool tuya_negotiate_session(tuya_device_t *" dev ", const char *" key ");"
.br
.BI "bool tuya_negotiate_session_start(tuya_device_t *" dev ", const char *" key ");"
.br
.BI "bool tuya_negotiate_session_finalize(tuya_device_t *" dev ","
.BI "    unsigned char *" buf ", int " size ", const char *" key ");"
.PP
.BI "char *tuya_set_value_bool(tuya_device_t *" dev ", int " dp ", bool " value ");"
.br
.BI "char *tuya_set_value_int(tuya_device_t *" dev ", int " dp ", int " value ");"
.br
.BI "char *tuya_set_value_string(tuya_device_t *" dev ", int " dp ","
.BI "    const char *" value ");"
.br
.BI "char *tuya_set_value_float(tuya_device_t *" dev ", int " dp ","
.BI "    double " value ");"
.PP
.BI "char *tuya_turn_on(tuya_device_t *" dev ", int " switch_dp ");"
.br
.BI "char *tuya_turn_off(tuya_device_t *" dev ", int " switch_dp ");"
.br
.BI "char *tuya_status(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "char *tuya_heartbeat(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.PP
.BI "int tuya_build_message(tuya_device_t *" dev ", unsigned char *" buf ","
.BI "    enum tuya_command " cmd ", const char *" payload ", const char *" key ");"
.br
.BI "char *tuya_decode_message(tuya_device_t *" dev ", unsigned char *" buf ","
.BI "    int " size ", const char *" key ");"
.br
.BI "char *tuya_generate_payload(tuya_device_t *" dev ","
.BI "    enum tuya_command " cmd ", const char *" device_id ","
.BI "    const char *" datapoints ");"
.PP
.BI "int tuya_send(tuya_device_t *" dev ", unsigned char *" buf ", int " size ");"
.br
.BI "int tuya_receive(tuya_device_t *" dev ", unsigned char *" buf ","
.BI "    int " maxsize ", int " minsize ");"
.PP
.BI "void tuya_free_string(char *" str ");"
.PP
.BI "void tuya_set_async_mode(tuya_device_t *" dev ", bool " async ");"
.br
.BI "bool tuya_is_socket_readable(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "bool tuya_is_socket_writable(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "bool tuya_set_session_ready(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.PP
.BI "enum tuya_protocol tuya_get_protocol(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "enum tuya_session_state tuya_get_session_state(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "enum tuya_socket_state tuya_get_socket_state(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "int tuya_get_last_error(tuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B seatuya
is a C wrapper around the tuyapp C++ library.
It provides a stable C ABI for communicating with Tuya / Smart Life
devices on the local network, supporting protocol versions 3.1, 3.3,
3.4, and 3.5.
.PP
The API has two tiers:
.TP
.B High-level (recommended)
Store credentials once with
.BR tuya_set_credentials (),
then use
.BR tuya_set_value_bool (),
.BR tuya_set_value_int (),
.BR tuya_turn_on (),
.BR tuya_status (),
etc.
Each call performs a complete round-trip (generate payload, encrypt,
send, receive, decrypt) and returns a malloc'd JSON response string.
.TP
.B Low-level
.BR tuya_generate_payload (),
.BR tuya_build_message (),
.BR tuya_send (),
.BR tuya_receive (),
and
.BR tuya_decode_message ()
give full control over each step.
Useful for pipelining, async workflows, or custom command types.
.SS Lifecycle
.BR tuya_create ()
allocates a device handle for the given protocol version
("3.1", "3.3", "3.4", or "3.5").
Returns NULL on invalid version.
The handle must be freed with
.BR tuya_destroy ().
.SS Credentials
.BR tuya_set_credentials ()
stores the device_id and local_key on the handle.
These are required by all high-level round-trip functions.
.BR tuya_get_device_id (),
.BR tuya_get_local_key (),
and
.BR tuya_get_ip ()
return the stored values (internal pointers -- do not free).
.SS Connection
.BR tuya_connect ()
opens a TCP connection to the device on port 6668 and stores the
IP internally for later use by
.BR tuya_reconnect ().
For protocol 3.4 and above, call
.BR tuya_negotiate_session ()
after connecting to establish an encrypted session.
For 3.1 and 3.3, session negotiation is a no-op.
.PP
.BR tuya_reconnect ()
re-establishes a dropped connection using the stored IP and
local_key.  For protocol 3.4+, it also re-negotiates the session.
If already connected, it returns immediately.
.SS High-level operations
.BR tuya_set_value_bool (),
.BR tuya_set_value_int (),
.BR tuya_set_value_string (),
and
.BR tuya_set_value_float ()
set a single data point on the device.
Each performs the full round-trip and returns a malloc'd JSON
response string, or NULL on error.
.PP
.BR tuya_turn_on ()
and
.BR tuya_turn_off ()
are convenience wrappers that set a boolean data point to true
or false.
.PP
.BR tuya_status ()
queries all data points from the device.
.PP
.BR tuya_heartbeat ()
sends a heartbeat to the device.
.PP
All returned strings must be freed with
.BR tuya_free_string ().
.SS Async mode
By default, receive calls block.
.BR tuya_set_async_mode ()
enables non-blocking operation.
When async mode is on,
.BR tuya_receive ()
returns immediately with \-1 if no data is available, and
.BR tuya_is_socket_readable ()
can be used to poll.
For protocol 3.4+, call
.BR tuya_set_session_ready ()
after async negotiation completes.
.SS Session negotiation
Protocol versions 3.4 and 3.5 require a key-exchange handshake before
encrypted communication can begin.
.BR tuya_negotiate_session ()
performs this in a single blocking call.
For async workflows, use
.BR tuya_negotiate_session_start ()
to send the initial handshake, then call
.BR tuya_negotiate_session_finalize ()
with the device's response.
.SS Low-level messages
.BR tuya_build_message ()
encrypts and frames a JSON payload for transmission.
.BR tuya_decode_message ()
decrypts a received response.
Both require the device's local encryption key (a 16-byte hex string
from the Tuya cloud).
.PP
.BR tuya_generate_payload ()
builds the JSON payload structure expected by the device for a given
command and set of data points.
.PP
Strings returned by
.BR tuya_decode_message ()
and
.BR tuya_generate_payload ()
are heap-allocated and must be freed with
.BR tuya_free_string ().
.SS State queries
.BR tuya_get_protocol (),
.BR tuya_get_session_state (),
.BR tuya_get_socket_state (),
and
.BR tuya_get_last_error ()
return the current state of the device handle.
.SH RETURN VALUES
.BR tuya_connect (),
.BR tuya_reconnect (),
.BR tuya_negotiate_session (),
and related session functions return
.B true
on success and
.B false
on failure.
.PP
.BR tuya_set_value_bool (),
.BR tuya_set_value_int (),
.BR tuya_set_value_string (),
.BR tuya_set_value_float (),
.BR tuya_turn_on (),
.BR tuya_turn_off (),
.BR tuya_status (),
and
.BR tuya_heartbeat ()
return a malloc'd JSON string on success, or NULL on error.
.PP
.BR tuya_build_message ()
returns the message size in bytes, or \-1 on error.
.PP
.BR tuya_send ()
and
.BR tuya_receive ()
return byte counts, or \-1 on error.
.SH EXAMPLES
Connect to a device and turn on data point 1 (high-level API):
.PP
.RS
.nf
tuya_device_t *dev = tuya_create("3.4");
tuya_set_credentials(dev, device_id, local_key);
tuya_connect(dev, "192.168.1.100");
tuya_negotiate_session(dev, local_key);

char *resp = tuya_turn_on(dev, 1);
printf("%s\\n", resp);
tuya_free_string(resp);

resp = tuya_status(dev);
printf("%s\\n", resp);
tuya_free_string(resp);

tuya_destroy(dev);
.fi
.RE
.PP
The same using the low-level API:
.PP
.RS
.nf
tuya_device_t *dev = tuya_create("3.4");
tuya_connect(dev, "192.168.1.100");
tuya_negotiate_session(dev, local_key);

char *payload = tuya_generate_payload(dev,
    TUYA_CMD_CONTROL, device_id, "{\\"1\\":true}");
unsigned char buf[1024];
int n = tuya_build_message(dev, buf,
    TUYA_CMD_CONTROL, payload, local_key);
tuya_free_string(payload);

tuya_send(dev, buf, n);
n = tuya_receive(dev, buf, sizeof buf, 0);
char *response = tuya_decode_message(dev, buf, n, local_key);
printf("%s\\n", response);
tuya_free_string(response);

tuya_destroy(dev);
.fi
.RE
.PP
The same workflow can be replicated from any language with FFI.
The newLISP bindings shipped with seatuya (seatuya.lsp) demonstrate
this: a thin module wraps the entire C API, and the example
programs (seatuya-wizard.lsp, sousvide-ramp.lsp) use it to control
real hardware without writing any C.
.SS newLISP convenience layer
.B seatuya.lsp
wraps the high-level C functions so the five-step round-trip is a
single call.
Store credentials once with
.BR tuya:set-credentials ,
then use
.BR tuya:set-value ,
.BR tuya:turn-on ,
.BR tuya:turn-off ,
.BR tuya:status ,
and
.BR tuya:heartbeat :
.PP
.RS
.nf
(load "seatuya.lsp")
(setq dev (tuya:create "3.3"))
(tuya:set-credentials dev device-id local-key)
(tuya:connect dev "192.168.1.50")
(tuya:set-value dev 1 true)     ; turn on DP 1
(tuya:status dev)                ; query all DPs
(tuya:destroy dev)
.fi
.RE
.SS newLISP FOOP device classes
.B tuya-devices.lsp
provides device-class convenience functions using newLISP FOOP
(Functional Object-Oriented Programming).
Each class maps named methods to the correct data point numbers
for that device category:
.PP
.RS
.nf
(load "tuya-devices.lsp")

; Smart plug
(setq plug (OutletDevice "3.3" "192.168.1.50" dev-id key))
(:turn-on plug)
(:turn-off plug)
(:destroy plug)

; RGB bulb (type B)
(setq bulb (BulbDevice "3.4" "192.168.1.51" dev-id key))
(:set-colour bulb 255 0 0)
(:set-brightness-pct bulb 50)
(:destroy bulb)
.fi
.RE
.PP
.BR OutletDevice ,
.BR BulbDevice ,
and
.BR CoverDevice
follow the same DP mappings as tinytuya's core device classes.
.BR ThermostatDevice ,
.BR SocketDevice ,
.BR ClimateDevice ,
.BR DoorbellDevice ,
.BR IRRemoteControlDevice ,
.BR InverterHeatPumpDevice ,
and
.BR PresenceDetectorDevice
follow their counterparts in tinytuya's community-contributed
.B Contrib
module.
.PP
All classes support
.B :status
(query DPs),
.B :reconnect
(re-establish a dropped connection, including session negotiation
for protocol 3.4+), and
.B :destroy
(disconnect and free).
Constructor arguments allow overriding default DP numbers
for devices with non-standard mappings.
.PP
The device handle stores credentials and IP internally.  The
FOOP objects also carry these fields for convenience, but the
C library is the source of truth for connection state and
round-trip operations.
.SH CONSTANTS
.TP
.B TUYA_DEFAULT_PORT
6668 (Tuya local protocol port).
.TP
.B TUYA_RECOMMENDED_BUFSIZE
1024 bytes.
